Assessing the impact of active case finding at the beginning of an outbreak

11 February, 2020

Aim

In this study, we use a simple conceptual model to study the conditions under which a mass testing strategy might be beneficial. This informs strategies currently being used in China in response to the 2019 nCoV outbreak. We explore the impact of this strategy on the population and individuals by considering the number of additional cases and deaths that may occur as a result. The goal is to help public health professionals make better decisions early in an outbreak even when there is a lack of basic information about the disease (e.g.basic reproduction number, latent or incubation period).

Introduction

At the beginning of many outbreaks, often only a small fraction of the total number of cases are found. To identify more cases, authorities frequently use passive or active case finding. In the current novel coronavirus (nCov) outbreak, China has conducted active case finding using symptom-based screening and testing.

However, the most effective control strategy should depend on the characteristics of the pathogen. The similarities of symptoms between nCov and other more common pathogens like influenza makes it nearly impossible to distinguish nCov without using a laboratory test. The issue of nosocomial infection between patients identified in the process of mass symptom-based screening may be an important source of new infections if there is risk of infection related to the testing process.

In the current nCov outbreak, with the fever clinics in Wuhan seeing around 10,000 patients per day, this risk should not be ignored. Patients diagnosed with the disease are isolated but patients with common infections are free to leave even though they may now be infected. If exposure in the waiting rooms of fever clinics and hospitals is leading to additional cases there is a serious question if mass symptom-based screening and testing is undermining the efforts to control the outbreak.

Method

Schematic diagram of the model

We consider a population of symptomatic patients. Among those with symptoms a proportion of infected with the novel pathogen (P1) the rest are infected with common pathogens (1-P1). In our model there are two pathways, one in which individuals with general symptoms stay at home (H), and one in which based on their symptoms they are sent to a health facility for testing (T) (Figure 1). When an infected person stays at home, the expected number of secondary infections caused by transmitting the novel pathogen is TH = T0*P1, where T0 is the average expected number of transmissions, i.e.the effective reproductive number. Similarly, a patient staying home has mortality risk due to the novel pathogen of MH = M0*P, where M0 is the risk of death if a person enters a healthcare facility under normal conditions, i.e.when they feel sick enough to seek medical treatment. In the second pathway individuals are required based on some pre-defined symptom-based screening, to be tested in a hospital or clinic. Patients whose test result is positive will be isolated and are assumed to not lead to further transmissions (T1 = 0). This is a conservative assumption, since it is reasonable that some transmission may occur even after isolation. Their mortality risk, M1, is reduced due to early diagnosis and treatment. However there is a probability (I) that patients not infected with the novel pathogen (1-P1), get infected during the testing process.

Parameters

We model the probability of infection during testing based on the proportion of novel pathogen infections (P1) and other risk factors (F) using this simple function I = P1* F/(1+ P1*F).

A patient who is not infected with the novel pathogen after the testing, will be considered negative and sent home. Susceptible patients who get infected during testing will also be free to leave since the test will not detect the new infection. For patients with a new infection the risk of transmission and death after testing is assumed to be the same as patients who stayed home (H).

We define the transmission risk ratio as TRR = TT/TH (transmission testing / transmission home) and the mortality risk ratio as MRR = MT/MH (mortality testing / mortality home). If the first ratio is larger than 1, it suggests that implementing a symptom-based mass testing program is not beneficial. Similarly, if the death risk ratio is greater than 1, it indicates that an individual patients probability of survival is not improved.

\[TRR = \frac{TT}{TH} = \frac{(1 - P1)\times F}{1 + F \times P1}\]

\[MRR = \frac{MT}{MH} = \frac{M1}{M0} + \frac{(1 - P1)\times F}{1 + F \times P1}\]

Parameters Meaning Value
P1 The proportion among those with symptoms who are infected with the novel pathogen in general population [0.01 - 1]
P2 The proportion among those found by screening who are infected with the novel pathogen = P1
F Risk factors in the mass screening and testing process [0.25 - 4]
I The probability of nosocomial infection (F * P2)/(1 + F * P2)
PT1 The diagnostic sensitivity of pathogen after the incubation period 1
PT2 The diagnostic sensitivity of pathogen at the 1st day of the incubation period 0

Results

Transmission risk ratio

The transmission risk ratio (TRR) depends on the proportion infected with common pathogens (1-P1), and transmission risk factors (F). The heat-map shows different values of P1 and F. We see that the gradient of TRR is unevenly distributed with F having substantial more influence than the values of P1. When P1 < 0.1, we find for most values of F the TRR increases quickly.

Contours for TRR decline

Mortality risk ratio

The mortality risk ratio (MRR) depends on the ratio of case fatality rate of the new pathogen (M1/M0), proportion infected with common pathogens (1-P1), and transmission risk factors (F). In scenarios, where M1/M0 ranges from 0.01 to 1, we find MRR is more often greater than 1. When M1/M0 = 0.8, MRR is only less than 1 only for values of P1 close to 1 and F below .3. As M1/M0 becomes smaller, MRR less than 1 for a larger range of both P1 and F values.

MRR Simulation in different scenarios

Discussion

In our model, the TRR is highly sensitive to the initial condition of the transmission risk factor (F). We denote F as a composite of all potential factors contributing to the risk of a susceptible person being infected by the emerging pathogen during testing. Depending on the scenario, a higher F could be taking public transportation and spending a long period of time in a crowded waiting room without enough personal protective equipment. Because of the heterogeneity of infection risks within the citys hospitals and clinics, identifying facilities with poor infection control could be critical to containing an outbreak early on. On the other hand, even the best hospital will have difficulties keeping F at a low level throughout an outbreak since the material demands can be extreme.

P1 is the proportion of the emerge pathogen infections among the total cases with similar symptoms identified by mass symptom-based screening. When an emerging infectious disease causes symptoms similar to common infections it is difficult to distinguish them when relying on symptoms alone. Like SARS, nCov shares similar symptoms with many other pathogens causing pneumonia (especially in flu season), if patients with fever and cough are required to be tested it is likely that many of the patients will not have coronavirus. If that is the case, it could lead to additional transmission and overwhelm even the most robust health care system. Other methods of delivering care such as Telehealth and Telemedicine may be better to either improve selection of patients with novel infections (increase P1 in testing facilities) or as the source of care for all but the most critically ill patients.

Mortality Risk Ratio (MRR) not only depends on TRR but also the ratio of M1/M0. In four scenarios we simulated, the mortality risk drop when the early diagnosis improves the prognosis. When M1/M0 is 0.1 or 0.05, mass testing based on symtpoms generally benefit the survival of patients. However, in the case of nCov, it is still unclear how much benefit the early diagnosis has so reducing the burden of death through a reduction in transmission maybe the better solution.

Containing an outbreak of an emerging pathogen by active case finding should consider the transmission risk factors (F) and the sensitivity of methods used to identify patients for testing (P1). If P1 is low, the authority should reduce the transmission risk factors (F) first, and suspend symptom-based screening and testing programs, and instead use Telehealth and Telemedicine to improve identification of patients (decrease (1-P1) in healthcare facilities) and allow time for the clinics and hospitals to prepare.
